07051nam a22009615i 9781783092710DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20142014enk    fo  d z      eng d  a2014021892  a97817830927107 a10.21832/97817830927102doi  a(DE-B1597)491463  a(OCoLC)897487497  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST00aP119.3b.L3585 2015 4aP119.3b.L3585 2015eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.44/948522300aLanguage Policies in Finland and Sweden :bInterdisciplinary and Multi-sited Comparisons /ced. by Mia Halonen, Pasi Ihalainen, Taina Saarinen. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMultilingual Matters00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tPart 1: Theoretical and Methodological Introduction -- t1. Diverse Discourses in Time and Space: Historical, Discourse Analytical and Ethnographic Approaches to Multi-sited Language Policy Discourse -- tPart 2: Language Policies in Parliaments, Legislation and the Media -- t2. Constructing ‘Language’ in Language Policy Discourse: Finnish and Swedish Legislative Processes in the 2000s -- t3. Building Walls or Bridges? A Language Ideological Debate About Bilingual Schools in Finland -- t4. Language Rights of the Russian-speaking Minority in Finland: Multi-sited Historical Arguments and Language Ideologies -- t5. The Art of Societal Ambivalence: A Retrospective View on Swedish Language Policies for Finnish in Sweden -- tPart 3: Individuals as Constructors and Reflectors of Language Policies -- t6. National Language Policy at the Local Level: The Realisation of Language Legislation in Late-19th-Century Finland -- t7. Making the Case for the Mother Tongue: Ethnic Activism and the Emergence of a New Policy Discourse on the Teaching of Non-Swedish Mother Tongues in Sweden in the 1960s and 1970s -- t8. Everyday Language Policies: Embodiment of Language-Related Experiences of Finnish Women in Sweden -- t9. ‘Listen, There’ll Be a Pause After Each Question’: A Swedish Lesson as a Nexus for Multi-sited Language Education Policies -- tPart 4: Epilogue -- t10. Epilogue: Multi-sited Language Policies – Where Have We Come From and Where To From Here in Language Policy? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume, authors from four disciplines join forces to develop an analysis of political discourse on a comparative and multidisciplinary basis. Language policy is often based on the political use of history, where the remembrance of past experiences by communities, individuals and historical bodies play a fundamental role. These authors see politics and policies as multi-sited by nature, taking place, being constructed, contested and reproduced simultaneously and in different times and places. Theoretically the book draws on the concept of language policy, operationalising it through the rhizomatic nature of politics and policies. Although confined empirically to considerations of situations in Finland and Sweden, the volume extends far beyond these locations in its theoretical contributions. The polities of Finland and Sweden are the lens through which a new and much needed understanding of language policy research, and policy research in general, is posited.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aComparative linguistics. 0aLanguage planningzFinland. 0aLanguage planningzSweden. 0aLanguage policyzFinland. 0aLanguage policyzSweden. 0aSociolinguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBoyd, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalonen, Mia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.